** The Difficult Balance of Intimacy and Independence: Beloved Philosopher=
 and Poet Kahlil Gibran on the Secret to a Loving and Lasting Relationship=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/27/kahlil-gibran-the-prophet-love-=
marriage/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0394404289/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db50=
39e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s the use of falling in love if you both remain iner=
tly as-you-were?=E2=80=9D Mary McCarthy asked her friend Hannah Arendt in=
 their correspondence about love (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/10=
/mary-mccarthy-hannah-arendt-love/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 . The question resonates because it speaks to a central necessity of love=
 =E2=80=94 at its truest and most potent=2C love invariably does change us=
=2C deconditioning our painful pathologies and elevating us toward our hig=
hest human potential. It allows us=2C as Barack Obama so eloquently wrote=
 in his reflections on what his mother taught him about love (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2016/06/13/barack-obama-dreams-from-my-father-love/?mc_c=
id=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C =E2=80=9Cto break across our solit=
ude=2C and then=2C if we=E2=80=99re lucky=2C [be] finally transformed int=
o something firmer.=E2=80=9D

But in the romantic ideal (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/30/skye-c=
leary-why-we-love-ted-ed/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) upon whi=
ch our modern mythos of love is built=2C the solidity of that togetherness=
 is taken to such an extreme as to render love fragile. When lovers are ex=
pected to fuse together so closely and completely=2C mutuality mutates int=
o a paralyzing codependence =E2=80=94 a calcified and rigid firmness that=
 becomes brittle to the possibility of growth. In the most nourishing kind=
 of love=2C the communion of togetherness coexists with an integrity of in=
dividuality=2C the two aspects always in dynamic and fluid dialogue. The p=
hilosopher Martin Heidegger captured this beautifully in his love letters=
 to Hannah Arendt (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/25/hannah-arendt-=
martin-heidegger-love-letters/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) :=
 =E2=80=9CWhy is love rich beyond all other possible human experiences and=
 a sweet burden to those seized in its grasp? Because we become what we lo=
ve and yet remain ourselves.=E2=80=9D

This difficult balance of intimacy and independence is what the great Leba=
nese-American artist=2C poet=2C and philosopher Kahlil Gibran (January 6=
=2C 1883=E2=80=93April 10=2C 1931) explores with uncommon insight and poet=
ic precision in a passage from his 1923 masterwork The Prophet (http://www=
=2Eamazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0394404289/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/prophet/o=
clc/1744006&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) ).

Illustration by Julie Paschkis from Pablo Neruda: Poet of the People (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2014/11/04/pablo-neruda-poet-of-the-people-book/=
?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Monica Brown

By way of advice on the secret to a loving and lasting marriage=2C Gibran=
 offers:

Let there be spaces in your togetherness=2C
And let the winds of the heavens dance between you.

Love one another but make not a bond of love:
Let it rather be a moving sea between the shores of your souls.
Fill each other=E2=80=99s cup but drink not from one cup.
Give one another of your bread but eat not from the same loaf.
Sing and dance together and be joyous=2C but let each one of you be alone=
=2C
Even as the strings of a lute are alone though they quiver with the same m=
usic.

Give your hearts=2C but not into each other=E2=80=99s keeping.
For only the hand of Life can contain your hearts.
And stand together=2C yet not too near together:
For the pillars of the temple stand apart=2C
And the oak tree and the cypress grow not in each other=E2=80=99s shadow.

Complement this particular portion of the wholly enchanting The Prophet (h=
ttp://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0394404289/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db503=
9e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with Virginia Woolf on what makes love last (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/11/virginia-woolf-on-relationships-mar=
riage/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C philosopher Alain Badio=
u on how we fall and stay in love (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/2=
6/alain-badiou-in-praise-of-love/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C Anna Dostoyevsky on the secret to a happy marriage (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2016/02/15/anna-dostoyevsky-reminiscences-marriage/?mc_cid=3D=
b5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Mary Oliver on how differences bring co=
uples closer together (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/09/10/mary-olive=
r-long-life-love-differences/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C=
 and Joseph Campbell on the single most important factor in sustaining rom=
antic relationships (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/06/29/pathways-to-=
bliss-joseph-campbell-marriage-relationships/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Gibran on the seeming self vs. the authenti=
c self
(https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/01/06/kahlil-gibran-madman-masks/?mc_c=
id=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and the absurdity of our self-righteou=
sness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/28/kahlil-gibran-the-madman-s=
aid-a-blade-of-grass/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


