** The Day I Became a Bird: A Tender Illustrated Parable of Falling in Lov=
e and Learning to Unmask Our True Selves (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
16/09/26/the-day-i-became-a-bird/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1771386215/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db50=
39e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

In what remains the greatest definition of love (https://www.brainpickings=
=2Eorg/2015/01/07/tom-stoppard-the-real-thing-love/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Tom Stoppard described the real thing as =E2=80=9Cknow=
ledge of each other=2C not of the flesh but through the flesh=2C knowledge=
 of self=2C the real him=2C the real her=2C in extremis=2C the mask slippe=
d from the face.=E2=80=9D And yet the grandest paradox of love =E2=80=94 t=
he source of its necessary frustration (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015=
/10/05/adam-phillips-missing-out-frustration-love/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the root of the inescapable lover=E2=80=99s sulk (htt=
ps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/27/alain-de-botton-the-course-of-love/?=
mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 is our insistence on cra=
fting and putting on ever more elaborate masks under the mistaken belief t=
hat these idealized selves=2C presented to the object of our infatuation=
=2C would render us more desirable and worthier of love. We tuck our messy=
 real selves behind polished veneers=2C orchestrate grand gestures=2C and=
 perform various psychoemotional acrobatics driven by the
illusion that love is something we must earn by what we do=2C rather than=
 something that comes to us unbidden simply for who we are.

The deconditioning of that dangerous delusion is what French children=E2=
=80=99s book author Ingrid Chabbert and Spanish artist Guridi explore with=
 imaginative subtlety in The Day I Became a Bird (http://www.amazon.com/ex=
ec/obidos/ASIN/1771386215/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/day-i-became-a-bird/ocl=
c/932093575&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) ).

The protagonist of this minimalist=2C maximally expressive story is a tend=
erhearted little boy who falls in love for the first time the day he start=
s school.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1771386215/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db50=
39e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

