** James Gleick on How Our Cultural Fascination with Time Travel Illuminat=
es Memory=2C the Nature of Time=2C and the Central Mystery of Human Consci=
ousness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/27/james-gleick-time-travel=
/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0307908798/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db50=
39e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CBoth in thought and in feeling=2C even though time be real=2C to=
 realise the unimportance of time is the gate of wisdom=2C=E2=80=9D Bertra=
nd Russell in 1931 as he made his beautiful case for =E2=80=9Ca largeness=
 of contemplation=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/13/bertr=
and-russell-mysticism-logic-time/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 in contemplating the nature of time. =E2=80=9CShard by shard we are relea=
sed from the tyranny of so-called time=2C=E2=80=9D Patti Smith wrote nearl=
y a century later in her magnificent meditation on time and transformation=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/19/patti-smith-m-train-loss-time/?=
mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

As a child in Bulgaria=2C never having heard of either Russell or Smith=2C=
 one aspect of time perplexed me to the point of obsession: In my history=
 textbooks=2C dates relating to significant events or historical figures o=
f Slavic origin were listed in pairs =E2=80=94 each had a =E2=80=9Cnew sty=
le=E2=80=9D date and an =E2=80=9Cold style=E2=80=9D date=2C always thirtee=
n days apart. So=2C for instance=2C Hristo Botev =E2=80=94 the great revol=
utionary who led Bulgaria=E2=80=99s liberation from a five-century Ottoman=
 slavery =E2=80=94 was born on January 6 of 1848 according to the new styl=
e and on Christmas Day of 1847 according to the old style.

I would later learn that this was the product of the League of Nations=2C=
 formed after WWI. Its Committee on Intellectual Cooperation=2C headed by=
 Henri Bergson =E2=80=94 the great French philosopher who famously opposed=
 Einstein in a debate that changed our modern conception of time (https://=
www.brainpickings.org/2015/12/09/the-physicist-and-the-philosopher-einstei=
n-bergson-jimena-canales/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=
=94 was tasked with eradicating the Julian calendar that many countries=2C=
 including Bulgaria and Russia=2C still used and replacing it with the Gre=
gorian calendar as the new global standard.

This is my earliest memory of confronting the nature of time as both an ab=
straction humans could make with a committee and a concrete anchor of exis=
tence mooring our births=2C our deaths=2C and our entire sense of history.=
 But most perplexing of all was the question of what happened to the peopl=
e who lived through the transition =E2=80=94 what happened to the thirteen=
 very real days between the two fictions of the calendars. If reading hist=
ory wasn=E2=80=99t time-travelish enough=2C reading about real people forc=
ed to time-travel in their real lives by an international decree was both=
 utterly fascinating and utterly confusing. Did the person actually exist=
 between their old-style date of birth and the new-style one =E2=80=94 wer=
e they alive or not-yet-born? (Even today=2C the Wikipedia biographies of=
 a Slavic persons from that era list both old-style and new-style dates of=
 birth and death.) The person=2C of course=2C most definitely did exist be=
tween the day they were born and the day they died=2C whatever dates
posterity =E2=80=94 our living present=2C their unlived future =E2=80=94 m=
ay impose on those days=2C now far in the past.

That thirteen-day lacuna between being and non-being was=2C apparently=2C=
 the price of globalization. But it was also a suddenly shrill echo of an=
 eternal question: If time bookends our existence=2C and if it is so easil=
y perturbed by a calendarical convention=2C is it a mere abstraction?

Discus chronologicus=2C a German depiction of time from the early 1720s=2C=
 from Cartographies of Time (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/02/07/cart=
ographies-of-time/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Time is the two-headed Baskerville hound chasing us as we run for our live=
s =E2=80=94 and from our lives =E2=80=94 driven by the twain terrors of te=
dium and urgency. Toward what=2C we dare not think. Meanwhile=2C our infor=
mation-input timelines are called =E2=80=9Cfeeds.=E2=80=9D We feast on tim=
e as time feasts on us. Time and information=2C if they are to be disentwi=
ned at all=2C dictate our lives. Is it any wonder=2C then=2C that we would=
 rebel by trying to subjugate them in return=2C whether by formalizing the=
m with our calendars or by fleeing from them with our time travel fantasie=
s?

How those time travel fantasies originated=2C what technological and cultu=
ral developments fomented this distinctly modern impulse of the collective=
 imagination=2C and how it illuminates our greatest anxieties is what scie=
nce historian and writer extraordinaire James Gleick explores in Time Trav=
el: A History (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0307908798/braipick-=
20?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.wor=
ldcat.org/title/time-travel-a-history/oclc/935983379&referer=3Dbrief_resul=
ts?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 a grand thought exp=
eriment=2C using physics and philosophy as the active agents=2C and litera=
ture as the catalyst. Embedded in the book is a bibliography for the Babel=
 of time =E2=80=94 a most exquisitely annotated compendium of the body of=
 time literature. What emerges is a inquiry=2C the most elegant since Borg=
es (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/a-new-refutation-of-time-borg=
es/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C into why we think about ti=
me=2C why its directionality troubles us so=2C and what asking these quest=
ions at all reveals about the
deepest mysteries of human consciousness and about what Gleick so beguilin=
gly calls =E2=80=9Cthe fast-expanding tapestry of interwoven ideas and fac=
ts that we call our culture.=E2=80=9D

Gleick=2C who examined the origin of our modern anxiety about time (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/11/james-gleick-faster/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b=
6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with remarkable prescience nearly two decades ago=2C=
 traces the invention of the notion of time travel to H.G. Wells=E2=80=99s=
 1895 masterpiece The Time Machine (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN=
/B004XVQ73G/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Although=
 Wells =E2=80=94 like Gleick=2C like any reputable physicist =E2=80=94 kne=
w that time travel was a scientific impossibility=2C he created an aesthet=
ic of thought which never previously existed and which has since shaped th=
e modern consciousness. Gleick argues that the art this aesthetic produced=
 =E2=80=94 an entire canon of time travel literature and film =E2=80=94 no=
t only permeated popular culture but even influenced some of the greatest=
 scientific minds of the past century=2C including Stephen Hawking (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2013/09/25/stephen-hawking-made-simple-animation/?=
mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C who once cleverly hosted a par=
ty for time travelers and when no one showed up
considered the impossibility of time travel proven=2C and John Archibald W=
heeler (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/02/it-from-bit-wheeler/?mc_c=
id=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C who popularized the term =E2=80=9C=
black hole=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/27/mapping-the-=
heavens-natarajan-black-holes/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and=
 coined =E2=80=9Cwormhole=2C=E2=80=9D both key tropes of time travel liter=
ature.

Illustration by Matthew Houston for a graphic interpretation of Wells=E2=
=80=99s The Time Machine (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/11/20/russ-ki=
ck-graphic-canon-of-childrens-literature/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[U=
NIQID])

Gleick considers how a scientific impossibility can become such fertile gr=
ound for the artistic imagination:

Why do we need time travel=2C when we already travel through space so far=
 and fast? For history. For mystery. For nostalgia. For hope. To examine o=
ur potential and explore our memories. To counter regret for the life we l=
ived=2C the only life=2C one dimension=2C beginning to end.

Wells=E2=80=99s Time Machine revealed a turning in the road=2C an alterati=
on in the human relationship with time. New technologies and ideas reinfor=
ced one another: the electric telegraph=2C the steam railroad=2C the earth=
 science of Lyell and the life science of Darwin=2C the rise of archeology=
 out of antiquarianism=2C and the perfection of clocks. When the nineteent=
h century turned to the twentieth=2C scientists and philosophers were prim=
ed to understand time in a new way. And so were we all. Time travel bloome=
d in the culture=2C its loops and twists and paradoxes.

Wells imagined time travel in an era where so much of what we take for gra=
nted was either a disorienting novelty or yet to be invented =E2=80=94 bic=
ycles=2C elevators=2C and balloons were new=2C and even the earliest visio=
ns of anything resembling the internet (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012=
/10/11/as-we-may-think-1945/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) were=
 half a century away. Gleick considers the direction of Wells=E2=80=99s im=
agination:

The object of Wells=E2=80=99s interest=2C bordering on obsession=2C was th=
e future =E2=80=94 that shadowy=2C inaccessible place. =E2=80=9CSo with a=
 kind of madness growing upon me=2C I flung myself into futurity=2C=E2=80=
=9D says the Time Traveller. Most people=2C Wells wrote =E2=80=94 =E2=80=
=9Cthe predominant type=2C the type of the majority of living people=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94 never think about the future. Or=2C if they do=2C they regar=
d it =E2=80=9Cas a sort of blank non-existence upon which the advancing pr=
esent will presently write events.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 The more modern sort=
 of person =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cthe creative=2C organizing=2C or masterful t=
ype=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 sees the future as our very reason for being: =E2=
=80=9CThings have been=2C says the legal mind=2C and so we are here. The c=
reative mind says we are here because things have yet to be.=E2=80=9D

Wells wrote his masterpiece shortly before the rise of relativity remodele=
d our notions of time (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/05/07/rebecca-go=
ldstein-incompleteness-godel-einstein-time/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) . There was Einstein=2C of course. And Kurt G=C3=B6del (https://=
www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/20/janna-levin-a-madman-dreams-of-turing-mac=
hines/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . And Hermann Minkowski=2C=
 Einstein=E2=80=99s teacher=2C whose model used four numbers (x=2C y=2C z=
=2C and t) to denote a =E2=80=9Cworld point=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 what we now=
 call spacetime. Gleick writes of his legacy:

=E2=80=9CMere shadows=2C=E2=80=9D Minkowski said. That was not mere poetry=
=2E He meant it almost literally. Our perceived reality is a projection=2C l=
ike the shadows projected by the fire in Plato=E2=80=99s cave (https://www=
=2Ebrainpickings.org/2015/03/23/plato-allegory-of-the-cave-ted-ed/?mc_cid=3D=
b5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . If the world =E2=80=94 the absolute world=
 =E2=80=94 is a four-dimensional continuum=2C then all that we perceive at=
 any instant is a slice of the whole. Our sense of time: an illusion. Noth=
ing passes; nothing changes. The universe =E2=80=94 the real universe=2C h=
idden from our blinkered sight =E2=80=94 comprises the totality of these t=
imeless=2C eternal world lines.

But if we were able to conceive of this timeless totality =E2=80=94 to int=
egrate it into our conscious experience =E2=80=94 the fantasy of time trav=
el wouldn=E2=80=99t scintillate us so. A centerpiece of our temporal disso=
nance is one particular phenomenon of consciousness=2C a very palpable hum=
an experience: memory. =E2=80=9CPerhaps memory is the time traveler=E2=80=
=99s subject=2C=E2=80=9D Gleick observes. With an eye to Virginia Woolf=E2=
=80=99s memorable mediation on memory (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/=
09/26/virginia-woolf-orlando-memory/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID=
]) in Orlando=2C that supreme masterwork of time travel=2C he writes:

What is memory=2C for a time traveler? A conundrum. We say that memory =E2=
=80=9Ctakes us back.=E2=80=9D Virginia Woolf called memory a seamstress=
 =E2=80=9Cand a capricious one at that.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 =E2=80=9CI can=
=E2=80=99t remember things before they happen=2C=E2=80=9D says Alice=2C an=
d the Queen retorts=2C =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a poor sort of memory that on=
ly works backwards.=E2=80=9D Memory both is and is not our past. It is not=
 recorded=2C as we sometimes imagine; it is made=2C and continually remade=
=2E If the time traveler meets herself=2C who remembers what=2C and when?

Illustration by Lisbeth Zwerger for a special edition of Alice in Wonderla=
nd (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/07/07/best-illustrations-alice-in-w=
onderland/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

The question of memory=2C of course=2C is inseparable from the question of=
 identity=2C for if we live in =E2=80=9Cpermanent present tense=2C=E2=80=
=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/08/permanent-present-tense-suza=
nne-corkin-h-m/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) we are incapable o=
f stringing together the narrative out of which our sense of self arises.=
 This continuity of selfhood=2C after all=2C is what makes you and your ch=
ildhood self the =E2=80=9Csame=E2=80=9D person (https://www.brainpickings.=
org/2014/10/07/rebecca-goldstein-personal-identity/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) despite a lifetime of physical and psychological change.=
 Time travel presents some serious paradoxes for memory and therefore for=
 the self. =E2=80=9CA person=E2=80=99s identity=2C=E2=80=9D Amin Maalouf w=
rote of the genes of the soul=2C (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/20=
/amin-maalouf-identity/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=9Ci=
s like a pattern drawn on a tightly stretched parchment. Touch just one pa=
rt of it=2C just one allegiance=2C and the whole person will react=2C the=
 whole drum will sound.=E2=80=9D If we could travel back to our own past a=
nd alter even a tiny
speck of the pattern=2C we=E2=80=99d be changing the entire drum =E2=80=94=
 our identity would have a wholly different sound. Gleick writes:

What is the self? A question for the twentieth century to ponder=2C from F=
reud to Hofstadter and Dennett with detours through Lacan=2C and time trav=
el provides some of the more profound variations on the theme. We have spl=
it personalities and alter egos galore. We have learned to doubt whether w=
e are our younger selves=2C whether we will be the same person when we nex=
t look. The literature of time travel =E2=80=A6 begins to offer a way into=
 questions that might otherwise belong to philosophers. It looks at them v=
iscerally and na=C3=AFvely =E2=80=94 as it were=2C nakedly.

And so we arrive=2C at page 99 and no sooner=2C at the problem of free wil=
l (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/25/sam-harris-free-will/?mc_cid=
=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Gleick writes:

Free will cannot be easily dismissed=2C because we experience it directly.=
 We make choices. No philosopher has yet sat down in a restaurant and told=
 the waiter=2C =E2=80=9CJust bring me whatever the universe has preordaine=
d.=E2=80=9D Then again=2C Einstein said that he could =E2=80=9Cwill=E2=80=
=9D himself to light his pipe without feeling particularly free. He liked=
 to quote Schopenhauer=E2=80=A6 Man can do what he will=2C but he cannot w=
ill what he wills.

The free will problem was a sleeping giant and=2C without particularly mea=
ning to=2C Einstein and Minkowski had prodded it awake. How literally were=
 their followers to take the space-time continuum =E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Cb=
lock universe=2C=E2=80=9D fixed for eternity=2C with our blinkered three-d=
imensional consciousnesses moving through it?

A century later=2C the question has hardly budged. And yet we live our liv=
es with such urgency and pointedness of intent =E2=80=94 perhaps precisely=
 because we are unwilling to relinquish the illusion of free will. Gleick=
 observes:

Everywhere we look=2C people are pressing elevator buttons (https://www.br=
ainpickings.org/2016/08/11/james-gleick-faster/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C turning doorknobs=2C hailing taxicabs=2C lifting sustena=
nce to their lips=2C and begging their lovers=E2=80=99 favor. We act as th=
ough the future is=2C if not in our control=2C not yet settled=E2=80=A6 We=
 would suffer illusions of free will=2C because=2C by happenstance=2C we t=
end to know less about the future than about the past.

Happenstance? Memory=2C self=2C free will =E2=80=94 this Venn diagram of c=
onsciousness is indeed encircled by the lines we draw=2C often artificiall=
y=2C between causality and chance. (=E2=80=9CNo one=E2=80=99s fated or doo=
med to love anyone=E2=80=A6 The accidents happen=2C=E2=80=9D wrote Adrienn=
e Rich (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/12/14/adrienne-rich-on-love-los=
s-happiness-creativity/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .) Gleick=
 writes:

All the paradoxes are time loops. They all force us to think about causali=
ty. Can an effect precede its cause? Of course not. Obviously. By definiti=
on.

[=E2=80=A6]

But we=E2=80=99re not very good at understanding causes. The first person=
 on record as trying to analyze cause and effect by power of ratiocination=
 was Aristotle=2C who created layers of complexity that have caused confus=
ion ever after. He distinguished four distinct types of causes=2C which ca=
n be named (making allowances for the impossibility of transmillennial tra=
nslation) the efficient=2C the formal=2C the material=2C and the final. So=
me of these are hard for us to recognize as causes. The efficient cause of=
 a sculpture is the sculptor=2C but the material cause is the marble. Both=
 are needed before the sculpture can exist. The final cause is the purpose=
 for which it is made =E2=80=94 its beauty=2C let=E2=80=99s say=E2=80=A6 W=
e do well to remember that nothing=2C when we look closely=2C has a single=
 unambiguous incontrovertible cause.

Gleick reality-checks the logicians=E2=80=99 causal models of reality:

If X=2C then Y means one thing in logic. In the physical world=2C it means=
 something trickier and always (we should know by now) subject to doubt. I=
n logic=2C it is rigid. In physics=2C there is slippage. Chance has a part=
 to play. Accidents can happen. Uncertainty is a principle. The world is m=
ore complex than any model.

[=E2=80=A6]

The physical laws are a construct=2C a convenience. They are not coextensi=
ve with the universe.

One of Antoine de Saint-Exup=C3=A9ry=E2=80=99s original watercolors for Th=
e Little Prince (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/02/03/exupery-little-p=
rince-morgan-drawings/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Mistaking the model for what Virginia Woolf called =E2=80=9Cthe thing itse=
lf=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/09/09/virginia-woolf-cotto=
n-wool-moments-of-being/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) seems to=
 be a perennial problem of science=2C and one particularly integral to the=
 perplexity of time:

William Faulkner said=2C =E2=80=9CThe aim of every artist is to arrest mot=
ion=2C which is life=2C by artificial means and hold it fixed.=E2=80=9D Sc=
ientists do that=2C too=2C and sometimes they forget they are using artifi=
cial means.

[=E2=80=A6]

You can say the equations of physics make no distinction between past and=
 future=2C between forward and backward in time. But if you do=2C you are=
 averting your gaze from the phenomena dearest to our hearts. You leave fo=
r another day or another department the puzzles of evolution=2C memory=2C=
 consciousness=2C life itself. Elementary processes may be reversible; com=
plex processes are not. In the world of things=2C time=E2=80=99s arrow is=
 always flying.

Illustration from a vintage children=E2=80=99s adaptation of Microm=C3=A9g=
as (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/14/micromegas-voltaire-elizabeth=
-hall/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Voltaire=E2=80=99s trai=
lblazing scifi homage to Newton

With an eye to Borges=E2=80=99s ideas about time (https://www.brainpicking=
s.org/2016/09/19/a-new-refutation-of-time-borges/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Gleick returns to the puzzlement of memory=2C equally=
 not coextensive with the physics of time:

We create memories or our memories create themselves. Consulting a memory=
 converts it into a memory of a memory. The memories of memories=2C the th=
oughts of thoughts=2C blend into one another until we cannot tease them ap=
art. Memory is recursive and self-referential. Mirrors. Mazes.

The formation of memory as a function of consciousness invites the chief r=
eligious opposition to science =E2=80=94 a theological avoidance of the fr=
ee will problem=2C the intellectually fragile contradictions of which Glei=
ck captures elegantly in discussing the ideas in Isaac Asimov=E2=80=99s no=
vel The End of Eternity:

Time is a feature of creation=2C and the creator remains apart from it=2C=
 transcendent over it. Does that mean that all our mortal time and history=
 is=2C for God=2C a mere instant =E2=80=94 complete and entire? For God ou=
tside of time=2C God in eternity=2C time does not pass; events do not occu=
r step by step; cause and effect are meaningless. He is not one-thing-afte=
r-another=2C but all-at-once. His =E2=80=9Cnow=E2=80=9D encompasses all ti=
me. Creation is a tapestry=2C or an Einsteinian block universe. Either way=
=2C one might believe that God sees it entire. For Him=2C the story does n=
ot have a beginning=2C middle=2C and end.

But if you believe in an interventionist god=2C what does that leave for h=
im to do? A changeless being is hard for us mortals to imagine. Does he ac=
t? Does he even think? Without sequential time=2C thought =E2=80=94 a proc=
ess =E2=80=94 is hard to imagine. Consciousness requires time=2C it seems.=
 It requires being in time. When we think=2C we seem to think consecutivel=
y=2C one thought leading to another=2C in timely fashion=2C forming memori=
es all the while. A god outside of time would not have memories. Omniscien=
ce doesn=E2=80=99t require them.

But whatever pitfalls=2C paradoxes=2C and perplexities might bedevil our i=
ndividual memory=2C they are rendered into even sharper relief in our coll=
ective memory =E2=80=94 nowhere more so than in the curious human obsessio=
n with time capsules=2C the grandest of which is the Golden Record (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2014/02/10/murmurs-of-earth-sagan-golden-record/?m=
c_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) that sailed into space aboard the V=
oyager in 1977=2C a civilizational labor of love dreamt up and rendered re=
al by Carl Sagan and Annie Druyan that was also the record of their own lo=
ve story (https://www.brainpickings.org/2011/12/27/the-voyagers-penny-lane=
-carl-sagan/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

The Golden Record (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/02/10/murmurs-of-ear=
th-sagan-golden-record/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Gleick considers what this strange millennia-old practice=2C this =E2=80=
=9Cprosthetic memory=2C=E2=80=9D reveals about human nature:

When people make time capsules=2C they disregard a vital fact of human his=
tory. Over the millennia =E2=80=94 slowly at first and then with gathering=
 speed =E2=80=94 we have evolved a collective methodology for saving infor=
mation about our lives and times and transmitting that information into th=
e future. We call it=2C for short=2C culture.

First came songs=2C clay pots=2C drawings on cave walls. Then tablets and=
 scrolls=2C paintings and books. Knots in alpaca threads=2C recording Inca=
n calendar data and tax receipts. These are external memory=2C extensions=
 of our biological selves. Mental prostheses. Then came repositories for t=
he preservation of these items: libraries=2C monasteries=2C museums; also=
 theater troupes and orchestras. They may consider their mission to be ent=
ertainment or spiritual practice or the celebration of beauty=2C but meanw=
hile they transmit our symbolic memory across the generations. We can reco=
gnize these institutions of culture as distributed storage and retrieval s=
ystems. The machinery is unreliable =E2=80=94 disorganized and discontinuo=
us=2C prone to failures and omissions. They use code. They require deciphe=
ring. Then again=2C whether made of stone=2C paper=2C or silicon=2C the te=
chnology of culture has a durability that the biological originals can onl=
y dream of. This is how we tell our descendants who we were.
By contrast=2C the recent smattering of time capsules is an oddball sidesh=
ow.

Building on the ideas he examined in his indispensable biography of inform=
ation (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/06/james-gleick-the-informati=
on-claude-shannon/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Gleick adds=
:

As for knowledge itself=2C that is our stock in trade. When the Library of=
 Alexandria burned=2C it was one of a kind. Now there are hundreds of thou=
sands=2C and they are crammed to overflowing. We have developed a species=
 memory. We leave our marks everywhere.

[=E2=80=A6]

When people fill time capsules they are trying to stop the clock =E2=80=94=
 take stock=2C freeze the now=2C arrest the incessant head-over-heels stam=
pede into the future. The past appears fixed=2C but memory=2C the fact of=
 it=2C or the process=2C is always in motion. That applies to our prosthet=
ic global memory as well as the biological version. When the Library of Co=
ngress promises to archive every tweet=2C does it create a Borgesian parad=
ox (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/a-new-refutation-of-time-borg=
es/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) in real time or a giant burial=
 chamber in progress?

Because time has this unsilenceable undertone reminding us of our morality=
=2C we grasp onto it =E2=80=94 onto this intangible abstraction =E2=80=94=
 the way we grasp onto material possessions=2C commodities=2C and all the=
 other tangibilia by which we sustain our illusions of permanence in a uni=
verse dominated by impermanence and constant flux (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2014/05/22/alan-lightman-accidental-universe-impermanence/?mc_cid=
=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . From this angle=2C Gleick revisits the=
 tenet that all paradoxes are time-loops:

Once we conceive of time as a quantity=2C we can store it up=2C apparently=
=2E We save it=2C spend it=2C accumulate it=2C and bank it. We do all this q=
uite obsessively nowadays=2C but the notion is at least four hundred years=
 old. Francis Bacon=2C 1612: =E2=80=9CTo choose Time=2C is to save Time.=
=E2=80=9D The corollary of saving time is wasting it.

[=E2=80=A6]

We go back and forth between being time=E2=80=99s master and its victim. T=
ime is ours to use=2C and then we are at its mercy. I wasted time=2C and n=
ow doth time waste me=2C says Richard II; For now hath time made me his nu=
mbering clock. If you say that an activity wastes time=2C implying a subst=
ance in finite supply=2C and then you say that it fills time=2C implying a=
 sort of container=2C have you contradicted yourself? Are you confused? Ar=
e you committing a failure of logic? None of those. On the contrary=2C you=
 are a clever creature=2C when it comes to time=2C and you can keep more t=
han one idea in your head. Language is imperfect; poetry=2C perfectly impe=
rfect. We can occupy the time and pass the time in the same breath. We can=
 devour time or languish in its slow-chapp=E2=80=99d power.

Still=2C memory remains. The key to understanding time=2C Gleick suggests=
=2C lies in understanding memory =E2=80=94 understanding the dialogue=2C o=
ften dissonant=2C between the experiencing self and the remembering self (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2011/10/26/thinking-fast-and-slow-daniel-kah=
neman/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . He writes:

The universe does what it does. We perceive change=2C perceive motion=2C a=
nd try to make sense of the teeming=2C blooming confusion. The hard proble=
m=2C in other words=2C is consciousness. We=E2=80=99re back where we start=
ed=2C with Wells=E2=80=99s Time Traveller=2C insisting that the only diffe=
rence between time and space is that =E2=80=9Cour consciousness moves alon=
g it=2C=E2=80=9D just before Einstein and Minkowski said the same. Physici=
sts have developed a love-hate relationship with the problem of the self.=
 On the one hand it=E2=80=99s none of their business =E2=80=94 leave it to=
 the (mere) psychologists. On the other hand=2C trying to extricate the ob=
server =E2=80=94 the measurer=2C the accumulator of information =E2=80=94=
 from the cool description of nature has turned out to be impossible. Our=
 consciousness is not some magical onlooker; it is a part of the universe=
 it tries to contemplate.

The mind is what we experience most immediately and what does the experien=
cing. It is subject to the arrow of time. It creates memories as it goes.=
 It models the world and continually compares these models with their pred=
ecessors. Whatever consciousness will turn out to be=2C it=E2=80=99s not a=
 moving flashlight illuminating successive slices of the four-dimensional=
 space-time continuum. It is a dynamical system=2C occurring in time=2C ev=
olving in time=2C able to absorb bits of information from the past and pro=
cess them=2C and able as well to create anticipation for the future.

[=E2=80=A6]

What is time? Things change=2C and time is how we keep track.

This act of keeping track=2C which is largely a matter of telling the pres=
ent from the past=2C is what Gleick considers the key question of consciou=
sness and the pillar of our very sense of self:

How do we construct the self? Can there be memory without consciousness? O=
bviously not. Or obviously. It depends what you mean by memory. A rat lear=
ns to run a maze =E2=80=94 does it remember the maze? If memory is the per=
petuation of information=2C then the least conscious of organisms possess=
 it. So do computers=2C whose memory we measure in bytes. So does a graves=
tone. But if memory is the action of recollection=2C the act of remembranc=
e=2C then it implies an ability to hold in the mind two constructs=2C one=
 representing the present and another representing the past=2C and to comp=
are them=2C one against the other. How did we learn to distinguish memory=
 from experience? When something misfires and we experience the present as=
 if it were a memory=2C we call that d=C3=A9j=C3=A0 vu. Considering d=C3=
=A9j=C3=A0 vu =E2=80=94 an illusion or pathology =E2=80=94 we might marvel=
 at the ordinary business of remembering.

This dizzying tour of science=2C philosophy=2C and their interaction with=
 literature is leading me to wonder: When a machine hums=2C does it hear o=
r notice the hum? Could it be that time is the hum of consciousness?

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0307908798/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db50=
39e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Perhaps time is so troublesome because it foists upon us our perennial fea=
r of missing out (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/17/missing-out-ada=
m-phillips/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Time travel=2C Gleic=
k argues=2C is such an alluring fantasy precisely because it bridges the i=
nfinite possibility of life with the realm of the probable =E2=80=94 by tr=
aveling in time=2C we get to live the myriad unlived lives which we are do=
omed to never experience under the physical laws of this one and only life=
 we=E2=80=99ve been allotted. He captures this with uncompromising precisi=
on:

If we have only the one universe =E2=80=94 if the universe is all there is=
 =E2=80=94 then time murders possibility. It erases the lives we might hav=
e had.

Time travel=2C then=2C is a thought experiment performed in the petri dish=
 of existence itself=2C catalyzing its most elemental and disquieting ques=
tions. In a reframing of the central idea of the Butterfly Effect =E2=80=
=94 a term Gleick himself wrested from the esoteric lexicon of meteorology=
 and embedded in the popular imagination in 1987 with his groundbreaking f=
irst book=2C Chaos (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0143113453/brai=
pick-20?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C which created an aesth=
etic for the history of science much like Wells created an aesthetic for t=
ime travel literature =E2=80=94 he considers the logical loops of changing=
 any one element of history=2C which ripples across all of being:

We have to ask these questions=2C don=E2=80=99t we? Is the world we have t=
he only world possible? Could everything have turned out differently? What=
 if you could not only kill Hitler and see what happens=2C but you could g=
o back again and again=2C making improvements=2C tweaking the timeline=2C=
 like the weatherman Phil (Bill Murray) in one of the greatest of all time=
-travel movies=2C reliving Groundhog Day until finally he gets it right.

Is this the best of all possible worlds? If you had a time machine=2C woul=
d you kill Hitler?

And so we arrive at the answer to the central question:

Why do we need time travel? All the answers come down to one. To elude dea=
th.

Time is a killer. Everyone knows that. Time will bury us. I wasted time=2C=
 and now doth time waste me. Time makes dust of all things. Time=E2=80=99s=
 winged chariot isn=E2=80=99t taking us anywhere good.

How aptly named=2C the time beyond death: the Hereafter.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0307908798/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db50=
39e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

But even death is strewn with the temporal asymmetry of our anxieties=2C w=
hich Montaigne articulated brilliantly half a millennium ago as he contemp=
lated death and the art of living (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/12/1=
2/montaigne-on-death-and-the-art-of-living/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) : =E2=80=9CTo lament that we shall not be alive a hundred years=
 hence=2C is the same folly as to be sorry we were not alive a hundred yea=
rs ago.=E2=80=9D And yet we do dread death with infinitely greater intensi=
ty than we dread=2C if that=E2=80=99s even the appropriate term=2C not hav=
ing lived before our birth. If the arrow of time is one-directional=2C so=
 is the arrow of time-anxiety. But Gleick subverts Montaigne and delivers=
 a sublime summation of the paradoxical impulse at the heart of our time t=
ravel yearnings:

You lived; you will always have lived. Death does not erase your life. It=
 is mere punctuation. If only time could be seen whole=2C then you could s=
ee the past remaining intact=2C instead of vanishing in the rearview mirro=
r. There is your immortality. Frozen in amber.

For me the price of denying death in this way is denying life.

Barring denial=2C our only recourse is to surrender our memory=2C our cons=
ciousness=2C our very selves to the flow of time. To borrow Sarah Manguso=
=E2=80=99s piercing observation=2C =E2=80=9Ctime punishes us by taking eve=
rything=2C but it also saves us =E2=80=94 by taking everything.=E2=80=9D (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/31/ongoingness-sarah-manguso/?mc_cid=
=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Gleick writes:

When the future vanishes into the past so quickly=2C what remains is a kin=
d of atemporality=2C a present tense in which temporal order feels as arbi=
trary as alphabetical order. We say that the present is real=E2=80=94yet i=
t flows through our fingers like quicksilver.

[=E2=80=A6]

It might be fair to say that all we perceive is change =E2=80=94 that any=
 sense of stasis is a constructed illusion. Every moment alters what came=
 before. We reach across layers of time for the memories of our memories.

Complement Time Travel (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0307908798/=
braipick-20?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 the kind of=
 book that lodges itself in the imagination=2C planting seeds of ideas=2C=
 insights=2C and revelations bound to go on blossoming for the remainder o=
f this lifetime =E2=80=94 with Bertrand Russell on the nature of time (htt=
ps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/13/bertrand-russell-mysticism-logic-tim=
e/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and Virginia Woolf on its aston=
ishing elasticity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/05/04/virginia-woolf=
-orlando-time/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Gl=
eick on the story behind Newton=E2=80=99s famous =E2=80=9Cstanding on the=
 shoulders of giants=E2=80=9D metaphor (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016=
/08/11/james-gleick-faster/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C th=
e source of Richard Feynman=E2=80=99s genius (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2016/05/11/richard-feynman-genius-james-gleick/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55b6&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and the origin of Type A (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2016/02/16/newton-standing-on-the-shoulders-of-giants/?mc_cid=3Db5039e55=
b6&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


