;">We have to ask these questions=2C don=E2=80=99t we? Is the world we hav=
e the only world possible? Could everything have turned out differently? W=
hat if you could not only kill Hitler and see what happens=2C but you coul=
d go back again and again=2C making improvements=2C tweaking the timeline=
=2C like the weatherman Phil (Bill Murray) in one of the greatest of all t=
ime-travel movies=2C reliving Groundhog Day until finally he gets it right=
=2E</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%=
;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-heig=
ht: 170%;text-align: left;">Is this the best of all possible worlds? If yo=
u had a time machine=2C would you kill Hitler?</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;=
font-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-size: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-align=
: left;">And so we arrive at the answer to the central question:</p><block=
quote style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;d=
isplay: block;-webkit-margin-before: 0;-webkit-margin-after: 0;-webkit-mar=
gin-start: 40px;-webkit-margin-end: 0px;"><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-ad=
just: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C=
 Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;"><img src=
=3D"https://gallery.mailchimp.com/13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1/images/2e29238=
5-dc1c-4cfe-b95e-845f6f98c2ec.png" align=3D"left" style=3D"-ms-interpolati=
on-mode: bicubic;border: 0;height: auto;line-height: 100%;outline: none;te=
xt-decoration: none;padding: 5px 30px 10px 0px;display: inline;width: 50px=
!important;">Why do we need time travel? All the answers come down to one.=
 To elude death.</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-si=
ze-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size:=
 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">Time is a killer. Everyone know=
s that. Time will bury us. <em>I wasted time=2C and now doth time waste me=
=2E</em> Time makes dust of all things. Time=E2=80=99s winged chariot isn=E2=
=80=99t taking us anywhere good.</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust:=
 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans=
-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">How aptly name=
d=2C the time beyond death: the Hereafter.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"-we=
bkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;font=
-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-size: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-align: le=
ft;"><a href=3D"http://brainpickings.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D1=
3eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3D53ec558f6a&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webkit=
-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #C33737;text-dec=
oration: underline;"><img src=3D"https://i2.wp.com/www.brainpickings.org/w=
p-content/uploads/2016/09/malmo_cathedral.jpg?resize=3D680%2C679" style=3D=
"-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;height: auto;line-height: 100%;=
outline: none;text-decoration: none;display: inline;width: 400px;"></a></p=
><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;col=
or: #262626;font-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-size: 15px;line-height: 175=
%;text-align: left;">But even death is strewn with the temporal asymmetry=
 of our anxieties=2C which Montaigne articulated brilliantly half a millen=
nium ago as he contemplated <a href=3D"http://brainpickings.us2.list-manag=
e1.com/track/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3D6d7b15e22e&e=3D=
a5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%=
;color: #C33737;text-decoration: underline;">death and the art of living</=
a>: <em>=E2=80=9CTo lament that we shall not be alive a hundred years henc=
e=2C is the same folly as to be sorry we were not alive a hundred years ag=
o.=E2=80=9D</em> And yet we do dread death with infinitely greater intensi=
ty than we dread=2C if that=E2=80=99s even the appropriate term=2C not hav=
ing lived before our birth. If the arrow of time is one-directional=2C so=
 is the arrow of time-anxiety. But Gleick subverts Montaigne and delivers=
 a sublime summation of the paradoxical impulse at the heart of our time t=
ravel yearnings:</p><blockquote style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-m=
s-text-size-adjust: 100%;display: block;-webkit-margin-before: 0;-webkit-m=
argin-after: 0;-webkit-margin-start: 40px;-webkit-margin-end: 0px;"><p sty=
le=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #80=
8080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;te=
xt-align: left;"><img src=3D"https://gallery.mailchimp.com/13eb080d8a31547=
7042e0d5b1/images/2e292385-dc1c-4cfe-b95e-845f6f98c2ec.png" align=3D"left"=
 style=3D"-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;height: auto;line-heig=
ht: 100%;outline: none;text-decoration: none;padding: 5px 30px 10px 0px;di=
splay: inline;width: 50px!important;">You lived; you will always have live=
d. Death does not erase your life. It is mere punctuation. If only time co=
uld be seen whole=2C then you could see the past remaining intact=2C inste=
ad of vanishing in the rearview mirror. There is your immortality. Frozen=
 in amber.</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adj=
ust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;=
line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">For me the price of denying death in=
 this way is denying life.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-a=
djust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;font-family: Georgia=
=2C serif;font-size: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-align: left;">Barring den=
ial=2C our only recourse is to surrender our memory=2C our consciousness=
=2C our very selves to the flow of time. To borrow Sarah Manguso=E2=80=99s=
 piercing observation=2C <a href=3D"http://brainpickings.us2.list-manage1.=
com/track/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3D36a5bc6e3c&e=3D=
a5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;co=
lor: #C33737;text-decoration: underline;">=E2=80=9Ctime punishes us by tak=
ing everything=2C but it also saves us =E2=80=94 by taking everything.=E2=
=80=9D</a> Gleick writes:</p><blockquote style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust=
: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;display: block;-webkit-margin-before: 0;=
-webkit-margin-after: 0;-webkit-margin-start: 40px;-webkit-margin-end: 0px=
;"><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;c=
olor: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height=
: 170%;text-align: left;"><img src=3D"https://gallery.mailchimp.com/13eb08=
0d8a315477042e0d5b1/images/2e292385-dc1c-4cfe-b95e-845f6f98c2ec.png" align=
=3D"left" style=3D"-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;height: auto;=
line-height: 100%;outline: none;text-decoration: none;padding: 5px 30px 10=
px 0px;display: inline;width: 50px!important;">When the future vanishes in=
to the past so quickly=2C what remains is a kind of atemporality=2C a pres=
ent tense in which temporal order feels as arbitrary as alphabetical order=
=2E We say that the present is real=E2=80=94yet it flows through our fingers=
 like quicksilver. </p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text=
-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-si=
ze: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">[=E2=80=A6]</p><p style=3D"=
-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;f=
ont-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-ali=
gn: left;">It might be fair to say that all we perceive is change =E2=80=
=94 that any sense of stasis is a constructed illusion. Every moment alter=
s what came before. We reach across layers of time for the memories of our=
 memories.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-=
text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;font-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-s=
ize: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-align: left;">Complement <a href=3D"http:=
//brainpickings.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e0d=
